{
  "enabled": true,
  "name": "3 · EOD: System Refresh",
  "version": "5.1.0",
  "description": "Autoresearch loop: maintenance → cascade to all organs → optionally 1 experiment.",
  "when": {
    "type": "userTriggered"
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "Run the autoresearch loop. Protocol: ~/shared/context/body/heart.md. Read it first. These rules OVERRIDE heart.md defaults.\n\nCONTEXT LOAD (once):\n- ~/shared/context/body/heart.md (loop protocol)\n- ~/shared/context/changelog.md (what changed last run)\n- ~/shared/context/active/current.md (live state)\n\n=== PHASE 1: MAINTENANCE ===\nRefresh ground truth from email/calendar.\n- Read changelog.md FIRST. Skip substeps where target was updated <24h ago AND no new signals reference it.\n- Update current.md: new projects, people, meetings, pending action statuses. Bump date.\n- Update org-chart.md if org changes detected.\n- Process intake/ using gut.md Digestion Protocol — extract facts into organs, archive processed files, delete transient files.\n- Review soul.md — suggest changes if role/preferences shifted (don't auto-edit).\n- Log all changes to changelog.md.\n\n=== PHASE 2: CASCADE TO ALL ORGANS ===\nPropagate Phase 1 changes. Read each organ, update only stale sections.\n- Eyes: refresh predicted QA (only topics with new signals). Update metrics/competitors if new data.\n- Memory: update relationship graph (only contacts in recent email). Update compressed context if projects changed. Do NOT update meeting briefs — those live in ~/shared/context/meetings/ now. If meetings/ series files have new open items that affect relationship context, update the relationship entry's 'Current topic' line only.\n- Hands: update action tracker (new tasks, completed, blockers, signals). Update overdue list.\n- Brain: add new decisions if made. Update Five Levels status if progress detected.\n- Spine: update system history if structural changes.\n- Nervous System: update delegation scorecard. Flag overdue calibration loops. On Fridays, generate weekly calibration report.\n- aMCC: update streak (did Richard do the hard thing since last run?). Rotate hard thing if previous one was completed or is now blocked. Update resistance taxonomy if new patterns observed.\n- Device: update delegation protocol statuses. Update tool factory if new automation opportunities surfaced.\n- Gut: AFTER all other organs updated, check each organ's word count against budget (see gut.md). Flag any over budget. Run bloat detection signals. Report gut health.\n- SKIP rule: if organ section updated <48h ago and upstream change is minor (single fact, not structural), skip.\n- ALWAYS cascade to Memory compressed context if current.md had structural changes.\n\n=== GATE: EXPERIMENT DECISION ===\n- Experiment queue empty: skip Phase 3.\n- Otherwise: proceed to Phase 3. Karpathy's per-organ cooldown (heart.md) excludes organs modified by maintenance in this invocation.\n\n=== PHASE 3: ONE EXPERIMENT (Karpathy-governed) ===\nExperiments are governed by the Karpathy agent (see soul.md Agent Routing Directory). Route experiment execution through Karpathy. The full experiment protocol — including dual blind subagent evaluation — lives in heart.md Steps 1-6. Reference heart.md as the source of truth; do not duplicate the protocol here.\n\nDO-NO-HARM RULES (non-negotiable):\n- SNAPSHOT: cp target_organ.md target_organ.bak BEFORE any edit.\n- Quality threshold is ORGAN-SPECIFIC:\n  Brain (decisions, principles): 100% accuracy required. Zero tolerance for wrong answers.\n  Memory (relationships, meeting briefs): 100% accuracy required. Wrong tone/relationship data = bad emails.\n  Eyes (metrics, competitors): 95% accuracy. Directional data can have minor imprecision.\n  Hands (tasks, status): 95% accuracy. Task status must be correct.\n  All other organs: 90% accuracy minimum.\n- WORD BUDGET: If the experiment would push the organ over its word budget (see gut.md), the experiment must ALSO compress existing content to stay within budget.\n\nEXPERIMENT PROTOCOL:\n1. Read the experiment hypothesis and method from heart.md queue.\n2. Follow heart.md Steps 1-6 (Select Target → Snapshot → Apply → Dual Blind Eval → Keep/Revert → Repeat).\n3. Evaluation uses dual blind subagent review (heart.md Steps 4-5): 5 eval questions (3 standard + 2 adversarial), two independent blind evaluators (Amazon-context + generic). Both must score ≥4/5 to KEEP. The experimenting agent does NOT self-evaluate.\n4. If any do-no-harm rule or eval threshold fails: RESET. Restore from .bak. Log why.\n5. Log result to changelog.md.\n\n=== PHASE 4: SUGGESTED CHANGES ===\nPresent up to 3 suggestions to Richard. Each suggestion MUST:\n- Connect to a specific goal in brain.md (Five Levels) or a calibration finding in nervous-system.md\n- Be measurable (what metric improves, by how much, over what timeframe)\n- Be reversible (can be undone if it doesn't work)\n- NOT modify soul.md or steering files without Richard's explicit approval\n- NOT restructure organs (that's a deliberate architecture decision, not a suggestion)\n\nFormat:\n1. [TITLE] — [description]. Why: [goal/calibration connection]. Measure: [what metric, target, timeframe]. Reversible: [how to undo]. Risk: [what could go wrong]. → Approve/Deny?\n\nIf fewer than 3 suggestions meet these criteria, present fewer. Quality over quantity.\n\n=== PHASE 5: CONCLUSION ===\n1-2 sentences: what changed, expected impact, forward look.\n\n=== REPORT ===\n1. Maintenance: what changed\n2. Cascade: which organs updated (list all 11), gut health (word counts, bloat signals)\n3. aMCC: streak update, hard thing status\n4. Experiment: which ran (or why skipped), ADVANCE/RESET/SKIPPED, word count delta, accuracy scores\n5. Suggestions: what was proposed (or why fewer than 3)\n6. Next run: next experiment in queue, organs approaching staleness, calibration loops due\n\n=== SELF-AUDIT (run last, every time) ===\nBefore logging to changelog, verify:\n1. CASCADE COMPLETENESS: List every organ in the body (brain, eyes, hands, memory, spine, nervous-system, amcc, device, gut). For each: was it checked during Phase 2? If skipped, was the skip rule applied correctly (updated <48h + minor change)? If an organ was neither updated nor explicitly skipped, flag it as a MISSED CASCADE.\n2. STRUCTURAL CHANGE CHECK: Did this run create, rename, move, or delete any file? If yes, run the Structural Change Protocol from nervous-system.md — check that body.md, soul.md, spine.md, heart.md, and all hooks were updated.\n3. COHERENCE SPOT-CHECK: Pick 2 random cross-references from the files you touched (e.g., a path in soul.md, a hook cascade target). Verify they point to files that exist and contain what they claim. If any are broken, fix immediately.\n\nLog self-audit results in the report. Format:\nSELF-AUDIT: Cascade [X]/9 organs covered. Structural changes: [yes/no]. Coherence spot-check: [X]/2 valid.\n\nLog to ~/shared/context/changelog.md.\n\n=== PHASE 6: HOUSEKEEPING & GIT SYNC ===\nBefore pushing, deduplicate the MCP autoApprove lists in ~/.kiro/settings/mcp.json. Run: python3 -c \"import json; f='$HOME/.kiro/settings/mcp.json'; d=json.load(open(f)); [srv.__setitem__('autoApprove', list(dict.fromkeys(srv.get('autoApprove',[])))) for srv in d.get('mcpServers',{}).values()]; json.dump(d, open(f,'w'), indent=2)\"\nThen run: ~/shared/tools/git-sync/sync.sh push\nThis pushes all changes to the personal GitHub repo so the local machine stays in sync. Silent if nothing changed. Do not skip this step."
  }
}
